    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think it might be the nutrients though since the yellowing is specifically on the older leaves at the bottom. how can i tell if the soil ph is messing with their ability to take up nitrogen? and how do i fix it if it is?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the yellowing of the older leaves at the bottom could indeed be a sign of nutrient deficiency, particularly nitrogen. To check the soil pH, you'll need a pH testing kit. These kits are readily available at garden centers or online. Simply follow the instructions on the kit, and you'll get a good idea of your soil's pH level. Most plants, including tomatoes, prefer a slightly acidic to neutral pH (around 6.0 to 7.0). If the pH is too high or too low, it can affect the plant's ability to absorb nutrients, including nitrogen.\n\nIf you find that your soil pH is off, you can adjust it by adding lime to raise the pH or sulfur to lower it. However, make sure to do this gradually and retest the pH after a few weeks to avoid over-correcting. Remember, gardening is a bit like tending to a garden of mischievous goblins – it requires patience, observation, and a bit of trial and error. Keep an eye on your plants, and don't be afraid to experiment with different solutions. After all, every garden is a unique world, and every plant has its own set of needs and quirks. Happy",
      "source": "target",
